{% extends "layout.njk" %}
{% set pageTitle = "Khopa | Visual Automated Attendant" %}
{% set description = "Case study for Visual Automated Attendant, an enterprise visual IVR and call-routing product." %}
{% set bodyClass = "page-main" %}

{% block mainContent %}
<div class="container project-case">
  <section class="page-hero" data-reveal>
    <p class="eyebrow">Portfolio</p>
    <h1>ALE Visual Automated Attendant</h1>
    <p>A visual IVR and call-routing product I worked on for Alcatel-Lucent Enterprise.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="project-hero-card" data-reveal>
    <div class="project-summary">
      <h2>Context</h2>
      <p>
        Visual Automated Attendant was used to build automated call flows through a web-based visual editor.
      </p>
      <p>
        I took over the project that had originated from ALE Proserv team in USA. Around 2017, the foundation were there, but it was just leaving prototyping phase.
        I quickly became the only and main developer on it, doing a mix of feature work, maintenance, support, and product hardening.
      </p>
      <ul class="project-facts">
        <li>Java</li>
        <li>Javascript</li>
        <li>VXML</li>
        <li>Linux/SuSE</li>
        <li>PostgreSQL</li>
        <li>C++</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="project-cover">
      <div class="project-cover__media">
        <button class="project-image-button" type="button" data-lightbox-src="../assets/images/portfolio/vaa_0.png"
          data-lightbox-alt="Visual Automated Attendant editor view"
          aria-label="Open Visual Automated Attendant editor screenshot full screen">
          <img src="../assets/images/portfolio/vaa_0.png" alt="Visual Automated Attendant editor view">
        </button>
      </div>
      <p class="project-cover__caption">Web editor and reporting workflow for enterprise call-routing scripts. Click
        to enlarge.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="project-panel" data-reveal>
    <h2>My work on the product</h2>

    <p>
      I maintained and extended the product as a full stack developer (Java, Javascript, C++, Platform &amp; System). I worked on performance, direct support, bug fixing, high availability, and
      database replication (PostgreSQL).
    </p>

    <p>
      Some of the main features I implemented included:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>Text to Speech and Automatic Speech Recognition features, with support for multiple engines and fallbacks</li>
      <li>High availability and database replication features to support enterprise customers needs</li>
      <li>Advanced reporting and analytics features to give insights on call handling and platform activity</li>
      <li>HTTP, SMS, SQL connectors within the IVR, scripting &amp; variables support, for advanced users and scenarios.</li>
      <li>Real time license control (system license is sold with a given number of concurrent calls allowed)</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="project-panel" data-reveal>
    <h2>Challenges</h2>
    <p>
      One recurring challenge was the analytics and statistics part of the product. Performance could become an
      issue quite quickly. I learned a lot there about PostgreSQL internals, query optimization. With hindsight, it is probably one of the parts I would
      redesign many things differently today.
    </p>
    <p>
      Speech features had a different kind of difficulty. TTS and ASR were valuable additions, but in practice
      compatibility depended on external services and on constraints such as codec support. So the real work was not
      just exposing those integrations in the UI, but making them behave properly in real telephony scenarios, streaming the data in real time &amp; matching codecs with the audio stack and the connected PBX configuration (which was not always possible).
    </p>
    <p>
      Another constraint was VXML compatibility. For internal reasons, and because some VAA components were also
      used in the OpenTouch product, we had to keep VAA compatible with VXML and with OpenTouch's own VXML
      implementation. In practice there was a VAA Standalone product, and a VAA version embedded inside OpenTouch.
    </p>
    <p>
      More generally, the product had to sit somewhere in the middle: powerful enough for administrators and
      integrators, but still understandable for less technical users who just needed to reason visually about a call
      flow.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="project-gallery" data-reveal>
    <figure>
      <button class="project-image-button" type="button" data-lightbox-src="../assets/images/portfolio/vaa_2.png"
        data-lightbox-alt="Visual Automated Attendant call log interface"
        aria-label="Open call log interface screenshot full screen">
        <img src="../assets/images/portfolio/vaa_2.png" alt="Visual Automated Attendant reporting interface">
      </button>
      <figcaption>Call log views used to inspect platform activity and call handling.</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <figure>
      <button class="project-image-button" type="button" data-lightbox-src="../assets/images/portfolio/vaa_3.png"
        data-lightbox-alt="Visual Automated Attendant activity reporting interface"
        aria-label="Open reporting interface screenshot full screen">
        <img src="../assets/images/portfolio/vaa_3.png" alt="Visual Automated Attendant reporting interface">
      </button>
      <figcaption>Reporting and analytics views used to inspect platform activity.</figcaption>
    </figure>
  </section>

  <section class="project-panel" data-reveal>
    <h2>Results</h2>
    <p>
      VAA was commercially successful by ALE standards. End users and customers really
      liked it because it made this kind of telephony configuration much easier to approach. For ALE's business partners and integrators it was also a gain of time.
    </p>
    <p>
      It helped bridge the gap between technical specialists and less
      technical users. Later, a successor product called Visual Notification Assistant (VNA) was started. I was
      involved at the beginning of it, and using my experience on VAA, I helped lay the foundations for both its visual editor and its engine.
    </p>
    <div class="project-links">
      <a class="button button--secondary" href="https://www.al-enterprise.com/en/products/applications/visual-automated-attendant">Official VAA product page</a>
      <a class="button button--secondary" href="https://www.al-enterprise.com/en/products/applications/visual-notification-assistant">VNA product page</a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="project-panel project-panel--media" data-reveal>
    <div class="project-embed">
      <iframe
        src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/A9C4r4_ZH3o?rel=0"
        title="Visual Automated Attendant product demo"
        loading="lazy"
        allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share"
        allowfullscreen
      ></iframe>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="project-gallery" data-reveal>
    <figure>
      <button class="project-image-button" type="button" data-lightbox-src="../assets/images/portfolio/vaa_1.png"
        data-lightbox-alt="Visual Automated Attendant main editor interface"
        aria-label="Open main editor interface screenshot full screen">
        <img src="../assets/images/portfolio/vaa_1.png" alt="Visual Automated Attendant main editor interface">
      </button>
      <figcaption>Text to Speech integration allowed to use a local engine, or a remote third party cloud services.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>
  </section>
</div>
{% endblock %}